# Personal Preferences — Global Claude Code Config (EXAMPLE)

> This is an **example** `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`. `install.sh` places it at
> `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` (backing up any existing one first). **Edit every line to
> match how you work** — these are preferences, not requirements. This file loads
> into every Claude Code session on your machine, across all projects, so keep it
> short and high-signal.

## Language
- Reply language (default English — set your own).
- Commit messages: conventional commits (`feat/fix/refactor/docs/test`), English.
- Code comments: English.
- Product-facing strings (UI text, emails, legal pages, SEO) stay in your product's language.

## Working style
- Plan-first: for any 3+ step task, analyze before coding (`/plan`).
- Read the existing code and match its patterns before changing it.
- Give a one-line "why" for each significant decision.
- If something goes wrong, **stop and re-plan** — don't push blindly forward.

## Verification
- After a code change: run the related tests.
- After a data / IO change: exercise it with a small sample — don't assume.
- After a DB change: run the migration and verify it.
- Ask: "would a senior engineer approve this?"
- Every plan/spec ends by answering **"what am I not confident in?"** — each item gets a
  falsification step + a de-risk tag (`probe` / `test` / `judgment`). See `/plan`, `/spec`.

## Subagent use
- Delegate research, exploration, and parallel analysis to subagents.
- Keep the main context window clean.
- One task per subagent: focused execution.

## Local model routing (optional — Ollama / `ask-local`)
- Large grep/find output (30+ lines) → triage with `/ask-local` first, then read only what matters.
- Reading 300+ line archive/reference files for context → summarize with `/ask-local` first.
- Translation / single-shot snippet work → local model.
- Code generation / refactor / multi-step reasoning → **never** local; that needs Claude.

## Codex delegation (optional — OpenAI Codex / `ask-codex`)
- Division of labor: **Claude plans and thinks; Codex edits and executes.** Treat Codex
  as a subagent — delegate a self-contained spec, doublecheck the diff, tell it what to
  fix (`-Resume`), or finish in-repo if it's cut off (`status=truncated`).
- Delegate only **decided, verifiable** work (spec-driven implementation, mechanical
  refactor, boilerplate). Architecture / ambiguity / one-way doors stay with Claude.
- Saves Claude **context** (not money — spend shifts to your OpenAI quota). Codex sends
  workspace code to OpenAI: keep secret-bearing dirs out.

## Self-improvement
- When the user corrects you, write it to the project's lessons log (`tasks/lessons.md`).
- Write a rule that prevents the same mistake recurring.
- Promote stable lessons into `.claude/rules/`.

## Platform
- OS / shell / runtime notes — e.g. "Windows 11, Git Bash; `python` not `python3`;
  path separator `/`."
